00:04:27,512 --> 00:04:33,093
There was a time, fairly like, I'm kind of ashamed at how far into the development, RuneScape

83
00:04:33,113 --> 00:04:34,054
didn't have source control.

84
00:04:34,694 --> 00:04:37,014
We had 100-odd developers all working from a network share.

85
00:04:37,294 --> 00:04:37,995
That's crazy, right?

86
00:04:39,643 --> 00:04:41,144
Actually it has a lot of benefits.

87
00:04:41,984 --> 00:04:45,606
You have access to everything everyone has done and is doing right now.

88
00:04:46,426 --> 00:04:49,308
The level of sharing and collaboration is incredible.

89
00:04:49,348 --> 00:04:51,269
The level of flexibility that you have is amazing.

90
00:04:52,049 --> 00:04:55,110
You don't have to worry about being able to, or what's your branching strategy or where

91
00:04:55,130 --> 00:04:56,371
are you going to grab a particular asset.

92
00:04:56,491 --> 00:04:57,832
Everything is available to you immediately.

93
00:04:58,232 --> 00:05:01,053
Sounds great, except for the fact that if anybody breaks anything on your login script

94
00:05:01,093 --> 00:05:02,554
the whole team is taken out, so that's not good.

95
00:05:03,805 --> 00:05:08,247
So we decided to change and we looked at how we could roll source control into a team while

96
00:05:08,287 --> 00:05:09,527
continuing to run a live service.

97
00:05:10,608 --> 00:05:13,149
I'm hoping no one ever has to do this by the way, it's an awful experience.

98
00:05:13,809 --> 00:05:17,251
Also you have to train everybody on how to use source control because many of them never

99
00:05:17,291 --> 00:05:19,072
had even seen it or knew it existed.

100
00:05:20,512 --> 00:05:22,853
And when we did make the change, that was difficult.

101
00:05:22,933 --> 00:05:25,195
Suddenly all that flexibility wasn't present.

102
00:05:26,144 --> 00:05:28,906
We had artists who were like, well, there's a texture that someone's using for an update

103
00:05:28,926 --> 00:05:29,646
that's coming out in a couple of...

104
00:05:29,666 --> 00:05:30,107
I want to use it.

105
00:05:30,127 --> 00:05:34,069
And you're like, well, that's coming out after yours, so we've got to plan around this now.

106
00:05:34,549 --> 00:05:38,392
And we started to put in all these processes and structures to improve things, and eventually

107
00:05:38,452 --> 00:05:38,932
it got better.

108
00:05:39,092 --> 00:05:42,254
We looked for those quick wins, or those early wins, and looked for those small changes to

109
00:05:42,274 --> 00:05:43,595
suggest we were going in the right direction.

110
00:05:44,456 --> 00:05:48,618
We had an easy one, the login scripts weren't being changed and knocking the entire team

111
00:05:48,638 --> 00:05:50,459
out every couple of minutes, so you know, that was good.

112
00:05:51,473 --> 00:05:56,355
But looking for those kinds of wins, uptime inside the development team, release cadence

113
00:05:56,395 --> 00:05:59,976
becoming stable, all that kind of structure coming into place, demonstrating to the team

114
00:05:59,996 --> 00:06:03,757
that the improvements were happening, allowed us to continue to improve to today where it

115
00:06:03,837 --> 00:06:06,237
is just our habits are formed again and everything is fine.

116
00:06:07,538 --> 00:06:12,359
If we had gone in without expecting to stumble and without expecting everything to be rosy

117
00:06:12,379 --> 00:06:16,820
and perfect at the start, that turnaround to bring the team on board would have been

118
00:06:16,860 --> 00:06:17,640
far more difficult.

119
00:06:17,680 --> 00:06:20,021
And I'm guessing a lot of people in this room have experienced something similar.

120
00:06:20,657 --> 00:06:22,038
in a different type of change in the past.

121
00:06:23,659 --> 00:06:28,482
But with this, some of the ways that we'll try and be able to support those kinds of

122
00:06:28,522 --> 00:06:31,664
changes in the future is our development environment and process itself.

