00:06:36,708 --> 00:06:38,689
I'll give everybody a bit of time to ask questions at the end.

126
00:06:39,857 --> 00:06:43,739
So if anybody knows Scrum, you'll see that we ripped these straight from Scrum.

127
00:06:44,019 --> 00:06:45,320
They're just the three pillars.

128
00:06:45,560 --> 00:06:46,460
But actually they're really good.

129
00:06:47,340 --> 00:06:50,462
We're talking about transparency, being open with information and open with each other

130
00:06:50,502 --> 00:06:51,582
on what's actually happening.

131
00:06:52,983 --> 00:06:56,864
Inspecting because being open is pointless if nobody's actually looking at that information.

132
00:06:57,225 --> 00:06:58,945
You're just generating random useless data.

133
00:06:59,706 --> 00:07:03,127
And then adaptation because inspection is pointless if you don't actually make a change.

134
00:07:03,167 --> 00:07:05,528
You're just sitting there having a discussion and then going away afterwards.

135
00:07:06,548 --> 00:07:09,170
So the three of these build on top of each other and the core of how we work.

136
00:07:10,928 --> 00:07:12,910
Let me go into each a little bit more in depth.

137
00:07:13,811 --> 00:07:17,675
To give you an idea of the level of transparency that we have at Jagex and why I say you can

138
00:07:17,795 --> 00:07:23,340
always be more open, our personal development and our objectives for each individual inside

139
00:07:23,361 --> 00:07:24,402
the organisation are open.

140
00:07:25,187 --> 00:07:29,633
For me, all of my objectives for the year are available for every single member of the

141
00:07:29,673 --> 00:07:30,314
company to see.

142
00:07:30,735 --> 00:07:35,421
Everyone from player support, QA, design, marketing, and my own direct reports know

143
00:07:35,461 --> 00:07:36,583
exactly what I'm trying to achieve.

144
00:07:37,244 --> 00:07:38,906
And they also know if I am achieving them.

145
00:07:39,187 --> 00:07:40,749
My progress and everything is available too.

146
00:07:42,075 --> 00:07:45,977
In terms of our products, every piece of data is available to anybody who works at Jagex.

147
00:07:46,277 --> 00:07:50,679
You can delve into our current conversion rates, our retention rates, all monetization

148
00:07:50,719 --> 00:07:55,721
detail and down into the individual little details around engagement in particular pieces

149
00:07:55,741 --> 00:07:58,042
of content that exists in RuneScape.

150
00:07:59,022 --> 00:08:01,483
That's the level of transparency that we try to get to.

151
00:08:02,283 --> 00:08:04,664
It's important that people are able to see how those things work.

152
00:08:06,785 --> 00:08:10,266
To try and get to this level of transparency, it's something that you can take on to yourself.

153
00:08:11,961 --> 00:08:16,364
If you are putting any piece of information together, for us the default is to be open

154
00:08:16,804 --> 00:08:19,126
and closing down access is the exception.

155
00:08:19,646 --> 00:08:23,829
For yourself, ask yourself why you're not sharing something wider, why you're only choosing

156
00:08:23,869 --> 00:08:25,530
a small subgroup to get involved in something.

157
00:08:26,110 --> 00:08:29,052
You don't have to tell everybody you're doing it, but don't lock down their access to it.

158
00:08:30,773 --> 00:08:33,255
You can also think about the time you're looking for information.

159
00:08:34,506 --> 00:08:37,108
And if it was difficult for you, what's going to happen when the next person looks for that

160
00:08:37,148 --> 00:08:37,828
piece of information?

161
00:08:38,489 --> 00:08:42,072
How can you make it easier for them to be able to find it and grow that culture of transparency

162
00:08:42,092 --> 00:08:42,992
inside your organisation?

163
00:08:43,933 --> 00:08:46,035
And then transparency is really tough.

164
00:08:46,395 --> 00:08:49,177
It's difficult to be open with everything that's going on.

165
00:08:49,217 --> 00:08:55,502
So being vulnerable yourself first will show those in your team that that's kind of the

166
00:08:55,522 --> 00:08:56,102
way that you want to work.

167
00:08:58,445 --> 00:09:04,252
To give you an idea of where we've used openness on RuneScape, let me go through a tough, harsh

168
00:09:04,312 --> 00:09:06,294
truth that we went through at the start of 2016.

169
00:09:06,374 --> 00:09:11,039
We launched a very significant update, trying to kick off the year.

170
00:09:11,159 --> 00:09:12,100
We brought out a new skill.

171
00:09:12,180 --> 00:09:16,465
And for anyone who's not aware, RuneScape has a number of skills that players can progress

172
00:09:16,525 --> 00:09:17,286
by engaging with them.

173
00:09:18,447 --> 00:09:21,030
Adding a new one is a significant amount of new content for somebody.

174
00:09:22,138 --> 00:09:25,240
And when it went out, we noticed that day one was really good.

175
00:09:25,661 --> 00:09:26,401
Reception was strong.

176
00:09:26,722 --> 00:09:28,183
People were enjoying what was there.

177
00:09:29,164 --> 00:09:30,925
But then we noticed the progression was way too fast.

178
00:09:30,945 --> 00:09:33,047
They were getting through the content very quickly.

179
00:09:33,667 --> 00:09:34,688
We half expected that.

180
00:09:35,449 --> 00:09:36,269
It was driven by wealth.

181
00:09:36,550 --> 00:09:38,031
People could just liquidate their wealth

182
00:09:38,071 --> 00:09:38,812
and get through the skill.

183
00:09:38,852 --> 00:09:41,494
We thought people would do that, but we had to look deeper.

184
00:09:42,334 --> 00:09:44,596
Now, RuneScape gathers about two terabytes of data every day.

185
00:09:45,477 --> 00:09:47,719
That's driving some of our heuristic analysis

186
00:09:47,839 --> 00:09:49,881
and a lot of the metrics that are given to the team.

187
00:09:50,862 --> 00:09:52,544
It meant that we had a lot of information coming back.

188
00:09:53,205 --> 00:09:55,307
But you'll see that when something bad is happening,

189
00:09:55,507 --> 00:09:57,549
a lot of people jump on assumptions and guesses.

190
00:09:58,070 --> 00:09:59,351
You'll have red herrings flying around.

191
00:09:59,871 --> 00:10:01,453
Having the level of transparency and openness

192
00:10:01,473 --> 00:10:02,975
in the information allowed us to cut those down

193
00:10:03,415 --> 00:10:04,977
and go directly to where the problem was happening.

194
00:10:05,397 --> 00:10:06,898
How are the people who are progressing fast

195
00:10:07,099 --> 00:10:08,100
really engaging with the game?

196
00:10:08,360 --> 00:10:09,381
What exactly are they doing?

197
00:10:10,120 --> 00:10:15,001
And that information allowed us to see the cause, identify a fix, and roll it out in

198
00:10:16,142 --> 00:10:19,083
an incredibly short time frame, which is immediately dropping out of my head right now.

199
00:10:20,303 --> 00:10:21,464
I think it was in a week or two.

200
00:10:21,804 --> 00:10:27,326
So the kind of cycle that we're doing on how we're altering the game is driven by the fact

201
00:10:27,346 --> 00:10:28,806
that the information is available to everybody.

202
00:10:29,827 --> 00:10:33,288
But of course, that required us to actually delve in and inspect the information.

203
00:10:34,328 --> 00:10:35,669
And data is...

204
00:10:36,586 --> 00:10:39,207
worth nothing if it's not observed and understood.

205
00:10:39,527 --> 00:10:43,369
Anybody can look at a page of stats, but understanding what those stats mean is the most important

206
00:10:43,409 --> 00:10:43,609
part.

207
00:10:46,711 --> 00:10:52,213
So another example of where we've used this in RuneScape and why it's important, the most

208
00:10:52,253 --> 00:10:56,996
important part for us in sprint cycle is the retrospective, that element where you come

209
00:10:57,036 --> 00:11:00,457
together and look at what's worked and what's not worked and how you can improve over time.

210
00:11:02,598 --> 00:11:06,940
We rolled out a marketing initiative, it's called Premier Club, it's a year's membership,

211
00:11:06,980 --> 00:11:09,781
it has perks, you'll be familiar with it for a lot of games.

212
00:11:11,141 --> 00:11:16,183
And one year it went reasonably well, the stats came back, they were strong, but we

213
00:11:16,203 --> 00:11:16,963
felt like we could do better.

214
00:11:17,104 --> 00:11:20,265
The process internally could have gone much better, there was some confusion, some conflict.

215
00:11:21,185 --> 00:11:24,186
So we ran a retrospective, gathered everybody together, we talked about what worked and

216
00:11:24,206 --> 00:11:24,686
what didn't work.

217
00:11:25,726 --> 00:11:30,850
We documented it, made it open, had some good honest open conversations about what we were

218
00:11:30,870 --> 00:11:33,692
going to do next and then we documented it and put it away.

219
00:11:34,392 --> 00:11:37,174
The important thing is coming back to that, inspecting it and understanding it.

220
00:11:37,815 --> 00:11:41,297
The next year we brought that back out when we were about to run the project again.

221
00:11:41,758 --> 00:11:43,019
It was like a letter from the future.

222
00:11:43,894 --> 00:11:45,975
Which was just telling us all the things we were about to do wrong.

223
00:11:46,675 --> 00:11:49,796
Allowing us to make sure that the next session was much better.

224
00:11:49,876 --> 00:11:50,336
And it was.

225
00:11:50,956 --> 00:11:52,217
The development was much smoother.

226
00:11:52,497 --> 00:11:54,057
There were no conflicts, there were no issues.

227
00:11:54,257 --> 00:11:55,538
People knew exactly what was going on.

228
00:11:55,598 --> 00:11:58,658
The communication lines that we needed in the first year were much better in the second

229
00:11:58,678 --> 00:11:58,819
year.

230
00:11:58,859 --> 00:12:00,179
And our performance was up as well.

231
00:12:00,839 --> 00:12:04,440
So we saw tangible change in the performance of the product, not just in the performance

232
00:12:04,460 --> 00:12:04,800
of the team.

233
00:12:06,141 --> 00:12:10,802
